          You have questions?  I have answers.  Well, *some* answers.
             For the answer to the meaning of life I charge money.
                     $80,- for a consult.  Well worth it.

Q1: What counts as a kill and what doesn't?
A1: Direct kills, including those at the beginning of the game, obviously count
    as kills.  So do indirect kills by bots and turrets you befriended, or
    killing people by throwing them off rooftops.  Killing stunned people also
    counts (obviously) as killing.  Smashing through a wall with someone behind
    it, snapping their neck, also counts as killing, so avoid these moments.
    
    Non-lethal takedowns, gas grenades and stun gun takedowns don't count as
    kills.  Bosses don't count and neither does destroying bots/turrets.

Q2: Where are the/teh hostages?
A2: Read the guide.  The same applies for any other question of which the
    answer can be found in this document, which should be the majority of
    questions.

Q3: Why do stealth and non-lethal kills give more experience than combat?
A3: Because Deus Ex Human Revolution differs from other games in that it wants
    to encourage stealth.  Besides the fact that straightforward combat is
    unrealistic for the (conspiracy) setting, there are already many shooters
    out there which are basically all the same:  You walk a few meters, kill
    someone.  You walk a few meters, kill a group of people.  You progress,
    you kill harder-to-kill enemies and bosses.  Perhaps the developers
    - rightfully so - didn't want people to just fight their way through their
    delicate game, and thus included many bonuses for stealth and non-lethal
    measures.  If you don't like this, you've bought the wrong game.  Don't
    worry though, surely there will be more than five brainless shoot-'em-ups
    coming out this year alone.

Q4: How do I shoot the ball through the basket to get the corresponding trophy/
    achievement?
A4: An easy way to do this (which requires Strength Enhancement) is to stack
    the nearby dumpsters in such a way so you can easily reach the basket.
    Simply hold the ball above the basket and release it (don't throw it),
    dropping it in the basket.

Q5: Is there a glitch to get infinite experience points?
A5: Yes, there is.  All you need to do is save your game in front of a PC,
    successfully hack it (preferably capturing the Diagnostic Subroutine to
    get all bonus rewards), then - leaving the XP notification on your screen -
    load your save game back up and repeat the process.  The best PC to do this
    on early in the game is Jensen's PC, which requires a LVL3 hacking skill,
    but it does give the most experience in the shortest time.  You will need a
    Nuke Virus and/or Stop! Worm Softwares to do reach the Diagnostic Subroutine
    in time, but one Nuke and two Stop! Worms do the trick, as do three Nukes.
    Jensen's PC will add 500 experience after every repetition.  Needless to
    say, this stacks rapidly.

Q6: Is it possible to max out experience/augmentations?
A6: Yes, it is possible; several people have done this already.  You will,
    however, be in the later stages of the game when you max out all augs.
    I don't know what the very earliest moment is that you can max out every
    single augmentation, so I hope someone will email me this answer soon.


Q7: Will you be doing any more guides after this one?
A7: No, probably not.

    Well, perhaps if they ever remake Final Fantasy VII.  Perhaps.
    [No, not perhaps.  Of course.]

    Or if something absolutely *fantastic* comes along.  Life is too short to
    play bad and boring videogames.  Not to mention write for bad videogames.

Everyone always seems to think about bigger better displays and things like that. But really, manipulating matter is easier than manipulating light. So the idea of cinematic holograms doesn't seem to be a likely course for the future. The same with other external hardware. I think that cybernetic implants along with nanite implanting is a lot more likely. Of course there's the ethical issue of programming for devices that interface directly with your body and brain. Perhaps open-source and a qualification of minimal programming skills should be a requesite for being able to have such devices interfacing with your body?

NANITES!!! Yep, nano machines inserted into the body with the directive of assembling ingested components into viable computer components. Seriously, the body already generates so much energy, just sitting and doing nothing. Why not harness some of that energy into making the human body better able to do anything. 

Alright, Nanites are still pretty far off. I've been looking into some stuff and it would seem that interfacing directly with nerves wouldn't be TOO hard. The optic nerve, that nerve  responsible for sight, seems like it would be a good place to work on. There's a lot going on in the world of VR and it really just makes more sense to me to interface direcly with the eyes. We could send signals through the optic nerves that would allow the brain to "see" something that isn't there. It would probably take a long time to figure out how to "render" an image to a persons brain, but the mechanics of nerve conductivity are well understood and so are the mechanics of HOW our senses work. The way that diferent nerves interpret stimulis from your environment.






Where did we come from? Is consciousness real? Do we have free will? Is the [[no-self|http://www.no-self.com/]] philosophy the best explanation? I don't buy it. In regards to the perceived universe, consciousness and God.

Lets state a few assumptions. Our percieved/experienced reality is the totality of what we have to draw on for emperical evidence. Anything beyond that is going to have to rely on analytical data examined and reasoned through with the rules of logic.

So, we step outside our universe and what is there? In the no-self concept, there would be a single consciousness. The no-self paradime stipulates, if the entirety of universe could be viewed then every moment; past present and future could be calculated. Therefore there is no free will. So far I take no exception and indeed say that their view is plausible. However, they fall into an exclusion fallacy with the conclusion, by extension, that if it's possible this is the only way it ''can'' be and discard any further argument, theory or debate.

I pose an alternative theory.

I think that if you step outside of our universe you'll find innumerable consciousnesses. Our reality would be held by one consciousness (God for lack of a better word) who has total and complete control of what he has created, other consciousneses may touch this reality, experience it by interacting and living a lifetime (human or not makes no difference so long as it's a conscious life). As the universe is the reality held by the godhead consciousness, other consciousnesses may choose to experience it in order to learn and grow their own consciousness by touching and not entering the reality. If they fully immersed their consciousness within the godhead reality then the no-self stipulation of a perfectly knowable and predictable future would continue. However, I envision the other consciousnesses to live their lives within this reality much the same as you can influence the patterns of smoke within a bubble by simply touching it on the outside. The godhead holds this bubble (reality) together and our lives are the poking of innumerable fingers (consciousnesses) against this bubble. In this manner, free will is maintained because the future is not able to be calculated. The observations of "now" can be future influenced by outside forces that are not observable in their entirety.

[[Utterly Reliable and Dependable]]








I'm thinking that a good place to start would be with my Humvee, 125 feet of chain, a strong stake and a scraper blade attached to the back of the Humvee. Drive the stake into the ground and attach the chain to the front of the Humvee, at one end, and the stake at the other end. Let the Humvee drive itself in circles pulling the blade scrapper in idle. You'll have a perfect circle started for the shaft. 

Phase 1 would be digging the shaft. I would want to dig down to bedrock and then excavate down an additional 500 feet for the main shaft. Obviously this is going to be somewhat deep and so the spiraling road down would need to be wide enough for 2 vehicles to pass. 30 feet should be good. 

Phase 2 would be digging out a much wider space, at the base of the shaft. This would be a sort of atrium, parking type of area. It could also be a good spot for initial living. 






What are the common traits of a person that puts them in one of these 2 positions? I'm sure that there's a lot of common ground between the 2 polarities.

<<<
''"If You Give a Mouse a Cookie"''<p>

If you give a mouse a cookie, he's going to ask for a glass of milk.<br>
When you give him the milk, he'll probably ask you for a straw.<br>
When he's finished, he'll ask you for a napkin.<br>
Then he'll want to look in a mirror to make sure he doesn't have a milk mustache.<br>
When he looks in the mirror, he might notice his hair needs a trim.<br>
So he'll probably ask for a pair of nail scissors.<br>
When he's finished giving himself a trim, he'll want a broom to sweep it up.<br>
He'll start sweeping.<br>
He might get carried away and sweep every room in the house.<br>
He may even end up washing the floors as well!<br>
When he's done, he'll probably want to take a nap.<br>
You'll have to fix up a little box for him with a blanket and a pillow.<br>
He'll crawl in, make himself comfortable and fluff the pillow a few times.<br>
He'll probably ask you to read him a story.<br>
So you'll read to him from one of your books, and he'll ask to see the pictures.<br>
When he looks at the pictures, he'll get so excited he'll want to sign his name with a pen.<br>
Then he'll want to hang his picture on your refrigerator.<br>
Which means he'll need Scotch tape. <br>
He'll hang up his drawing and stand back to look at it.<br>
Looking at the refrigerator will remind him that he's thirsty.<br>
So... he'll ask for a glass of milk.<br>
And chances are if he asks you for a glass of milk, he's going to want a cookie to go with it.<br>

â€œIf you love someone, then your freedom is curtailed. If you love someone, you give up much of your privacy. If you love someone, then you are no longer merely one person but half of a couple. To think or behave any other way is to risk losing that love.â€






Charles Lugtu

To the new Husband of my children's Mother,

When you were 7 years old I met a woman that I madly fell in love with, the same woman that I understand you recently married. I am writing today in the hopes that you will be sparred the pain and heartache that plagued my 15 year relationship with her.

As with all relationships, it began with a series of long lingering looks. We met at Junior College through mutual friends. At that time, she was the girlfriend of one of my friends. I don't believe in poaching my friends girlfriends and things continued in that fashion for a while. I would go over to one of our friends houses for a game night and our eyes would meet across the game table and, to my shame, I shared long lingering glances with her from across the game table. What I should have done no longer matters, to live in the past with regrets is not really living at all. Our relationship escalated one day when I was high on drugs and let down my inhibitions about poaching and finally kissed her in the back yard of our friends house, while her boyfriend was in the other room with our mutual friend of that time.

Nothing else happened between us for close to 6 months while I tortured myself over the fact that I had givin in to my physical desires for a compelling woman. She was into all of the things that I was into and seemed like the perfect match for me. We would talk and she and her boyfriend actually helped my to move to my very first apartment in Van Nuys. In January of 1999 she called me up one day in tears (we had been talking to each other on the phone for some time) and explained that she wanted to get out of the place she was staying because she and her boyfriend had just had THE fight and she didn't want to be there at that time. Obligingly, I went over and picked her up and brought her back to my apartment. We talked for some time and one thing led to another and we ended up having sex for the first time there on my living room floor. It took close to 3 months for her to stop living with her boyfriend and I became boyfriend on the side during that time. She finally moved out of her housing and into the home of some of our other friends in Santa Monica. Things seemed to be going great for a year and we just grew closer and closer as a couple. In late February of 2000 I moved to Chicago to get away from myself and the life that I had been living. I had offered to bring her with me, tearfully she told me that she couldn't go at that time but we arranged that I would bring her out once I was settled out there. I wrote to her every day for the 3 months I was out there. In May, I received a "Dear John" email from her telling me that she wouldn't come out to Chicago with me. I immediately called up some friends and called in a favor. I had a job secured within a day, packed my bags and was back in LA less than a week later. I moved in with her and our mutual friends in Santa Monica, which was convenient because the job I had located was in Venice Beach. Over the next 3 months we worked on getting our lives back together and I bought a ring to propose with.

At her 21'st birthday party, I became enraged with jealousy and too much alcohol. I don't remember what happened, I was that drunk, but apparently I made a considerable fool of myself. Well, a couple days later I finally worked up the nerve to ask her to marry me, after we had made up for my behavior at her birthday party. She said yes, I gave her the ring and then a few hours later she came back to me and returned the ring. I was devastated and heartbroken. I had family pick me up and I moved out that day. As time passed, I missed her and so we started talking again. Without me, the shared apartment couldn't make rent so she ended up moving in with our friends in Canoga Park. Around March of 2011 I believed that we had made up. We were seeing each other again, she had found a job in Newburry Park and we could see each other at my parents house after she finished work. I had mistakenly assumed that because we were intimate that she wasn't with anyone else. After we had been together a few times she informed me that she had slept with another man who lived in that house with them. I was bothered by it, but I did my best to let it go as we were getting along well again. Around May we found out that she was pregnant with our first. I knew that she had been pregnant twice before and that she had terminated those pregnancies prematurely. When we discussed her pregnancy with our first, she informed me that she was considering abortion for this pregnancy as well. I was outraged and informed her that if she did that, I would have nothing to do with her ever again. Instead we had a great time getting married in August of that year.

The next few years were tough, as they always are for newly weds of our age with children. She had some serious health issues that plauged her. I worked nights during that time and it was very lonely. I had nothing to do all night but spend time chatting. I always chatted in the "Christian" chat rooms on Yahoo, but eventually I ended up speaking privately with women in foreign countries, mostly flirting but sometimes going beyond the limits of propriety. I justified my actions by telling myself that I wasn't really cheating because these were women that I would never meet and so it didn't matter. Of course she found out and was quite upset and justifiably so. We talked and worked things out. Things were going OK until after we got back from a trip to Michigan to visit my family. A few days after we were back, I noticed that she was acting kinda weird. I asked about it and was informed that my dad had kissed her on that trip. I was enraged and ready to commit murder. Instead I called a meeting with him and asked him to discuss the issue and see how he was going to make amends. We worked things out but I vowed that he would never again be alone with my wife. Fast forward a few years and my daughter is now born. I'm still working nights and her health is quickly declining. We are spending more and more time at the emergency room and doctors visits trying to figure out whats wrong. On the last of these visits she is admitted to Cedar Sania Hospital due to blood loss. I am standing outside the building that she is in after we authorize the first of her blood transfusions. I'm praying as hard as I can that she doesn't die when the doctor comes out and informs me that she is bleeding out faster than they can get blood in her. They tell me that they have consulted with the surgeon and that they recommend an immediate colostomy. I'm further advised that they have asked her consent for the surgery but they don't feel that she is capable of making that decision at this time and would like me to make the decision to save her life. Of course I opt to save her. The next few months are a blur I'm taking care of the kids by myself working and spending time at the hospital, as can be expected eventually I just can't do it any more. After she returned home after the first surgery we move back in with my family. It was never comfortable living there, but you do what you have to do. Time goes by, eventually we have a place of our own but I loose my job and can't find work. This was during the market crash and we ended up moving in with her mom and her moms husband. Things are tense from the get go there. Her health is still less than ideal. I feel like I'm drowning in debt for the surgery I'm trying to find work and keep work while all the while I'm trying to hold in my building resentment for not being appreciated for all the effort I put into keeping us together. So, being already less than fully sane, I finally snap and go full blown manic for a while between February and April 2009, when I run out of medication and can't get more because of a lack of heath insurance. During that time I moved out, blew $10k on God knows what and generally screwed myself 10 ways to Tuesday. When I came back to my senses, I tried to fix things. I made apologies all around. I worked to bring her and my children back into my life as hard as I've tried anything in my life. In fact I did so until the end of October 2013. I tried everything, marriage counseling (eventually ended, as the counselor remarked at our last visit. It takes both parts of the couple to heal). I had many many therapy sessions, as well as live in therapy where I really did a lot of work on me and made great progress.

Well, all this brings me to my conclusion. The definition of insanity is doing the same thing repeatedly expecting a different result. I tried many things, many different ways to resolve issues and so I am not insane, even though the outcome was always the same. Unfortunately, she has not learned this lesson and you are her latest victim. She managed to go about 15 years before repeating her pattern, but repeat it she did with you. I don't know what happened before me. But, it's har to deny that she isn't doing the same thing again. And the results are still going to be the same.

Since our divorce was made final on 08/13/2014 I have grown a lot as a person. I'm still single, I've been on a few dates, but I'm not overly concerned with having an intimate relationship with another woman at this time. I'm happy and relatively stress free. With the lack of stress, the symptoms of my medical condition seem to have dissipated so long as I maintain my physical health, medication and lifestyle. You see, I've come to realize that never being enough, never having enough and never feeling enough wore me down and broke apart my sense of self and eventually my sanity. Hopefully the same doesn't happen to you.






Premise: All life is precious and the pursuit of happiness is an inherent right of all life. 






Lilly,

Hello my darling daughter. I hope this letter finds you well, on your fifteenth birthday. Fifteen is a pretty big deal... You're halfway to thirty and you're one fouth the way to sixty!

There are plenty of things that I wish were different. One of those is that I would prefer to be able to spend more time with you and your brothers. I don't get to see any of you as much as I would prefer. I do try to keep in contact, but for whatever the reason I seem to have failed with you. I feel sad about this. I don't know you, as a person, the way I'd prefer. I hope that this will change in time.

My hope for you is that you will have a beautiful and happy life. 

Love always, 
Dad

The tenets of faith are intrinsic and eternal. However; it seems that the failing of religion is that the practices of the faith are based on a time or situation. It would seem that proper course for the development of a religion is to makes the practice of the faith able to be changed to accommodate the environment while the tenets are maintained.

Thinking more about religion. I was raised Christian. I've been reading Plato and it's really interesting how the life of Jesus resembles the life of Socrates. Thinking about Christianity and all, I have to ask myself about the origin of the religion in Judaism and then the origin of Judaism itself. In the Bible, the recurring themes are that humans are not perfect and only through the intervention of the divine can we obtain eternity (translated in my mind to enlightenment). It's actually a fairly common theme in all the religions I've studied, at least at the root of the religion. At the root of religion is the effort humans put into themselves to be at peace in the end. 






I once spoke with a shrink about suicide. He had a personal observation that he shared with me. He told told me that every suicide he's ever seen has been motivated by anger. The messier the suicide, the more angry the person was. Too, you can tell the direction of the anger by whether or not the anger was at themselves or at others. A person who blows their head off is angry with themselves or just in general. A murder/suicide is angry with their target. Yes, depression is the leading cause of suicide, but anger is the motivation.

People who have never had to survive crippling depression don't understand. They don't understand that anger is the only fuel that will get us out of bed and functioning for the day. They don't understand that anger helps us to feel alive when we're already dead inside. To anyone who reads this and is suffering from depression, your anger will serve you to a point but then it will destroy you and the lives of everyone around you. Get help. Let go of your anger. Embrace your sadness and understand it. Learn and you WILL find your joy again. You can do it, but you need help to get there. NONE of us are meant to do everything alone.






On the one hand, I agree with Douglas Adams in that the leader of the universe should be completely without emotion or influence of the universe he leads. On the other hand, EVERYONE should be exposed to as much philosophy as possible and as many different ideas as possible so that they can be informed when it's time to make decisions of their own.

Humans have long held that they are the top of the evolutionary ladder on our planet. We breed livestock and other animals selectively, not to mention plant life, yet we leave our own future to no better than chance. Should we find a way to be more objective in our future as a species?

So thinking more about this, we have to take into account what I'm calling the "Gatica" effect. These thoughts came when I was thinking about after reading this article: https://goo.gl/nQfCrN






&#35;neverforget

When telling this story, a lot of people start with "My day started just like any other", but not mine. I was newly married and my wife was 6 months pregnant with my first born. I was in the process of changing my career industry. Before I got married, I had decided that working in the entertainment industry wasn't a stable enough environment to raise a family. In the interim, I was working for my now father-in-law doing construction. I had only been working for a few days at a job in Malibu. Lanny (my father-in-law) had sent me to the hardware store with a blank check to get some things we needed for the days work. On the way to the hardware store, I got a txt from my mom saying that her flight had been delayed and they didn't know when their flight would be leaving, well nothing really too odd about that. When I got to the hardware store, a lot of people were watching TV in the store, in retrospect they looked shocked, but I didn't think too much or even really notice. I did my shopping, nails and the such, and when I got to the checkout line I didn't have anything better to do than watch the TV while I was waiting to place my items on the counter and check-out.

There was a shot of the Twin Towers, in New York, playing over and over on a loop. There was no audio, just video. Having just come out of "The Industry" I thought it was pretty good CG of a plane colliding with the towers, but I didn't know why they were playing it on a loop. I asked the woman at check-out what was going on, and that's when my perception of reality changed.

That one event in the history of the world changed me, permanently and irrevocably. I was 21. Many of us know what I felt at that announcement. It's 17 years later now. We have an entire generation who didn't experience what we all felt that day and the weeks following. Our countries leadership responded swiftly and with vengeance. In the days and weeks following I was reminded of the quote attributed to //Isoroku Yamamoto//:

<<<
"I fear all we have done is to awaken a sleeping giant and fill him with a terrible resolve."
<<<

This in response to Japans attack on Perl Harbor.

For the last 17 years the Giant that is the United States Military has rampaged around the world killing with an almost indiscriminate and callous ease. In our grief, we have killed untold numbers of people, many of them innocent of any wrong doing.

For the last 17 years, on this day and every day in between, I have sublimed my emotion. I have turned my grief to anger (as I have felt in the past a justified anger) bordering on hate. ''I WILL NOT DO IT ANYMORE.'' I ''will'' grieve. I ''will'' feel my pain. I ''will'' heal this wound that has been festering and eating at me. I have no more hate or anger to give. I have only grief and compassion left. Grief for my losses in the last 17 years. Grief for my callous attitude towards everyone in the world who has suffered for no reason because of this event.

As 1 person of 380 million who hold the leash of this monster, I beg everyone else who holds this leash to help me reign it in and put it back to sleep. Our vengeance is complete, we need to heal as a people of our terrible wound.

Where did it all start? Who is the genius who invented the nano-machines and figured out how to use them to build an interface with the human mind. There's something odd about this guy that should probably remain a mystery.

I was born in the year 1680. However, I stopped aging in the year 1708. I can't explain it, belive me I've tried. But I did come up with some interesting knowledge during my years. It's now 2063 and I'm ready to move. 






Well, this is a shitter... I seem to have lost my plot. Not that it matters //too// much, I never did get my ideas strait. My story will span thousands of eons, and no //real// date really matters. We'll have dragons and magic and technology to make you weep. I'm thinking we'll start with an advanced Earth that is in it's final death throws. Humans have become augmented to the point where nannites now influence humans almost to an atomic level. Because of this level of bonding with machinery, humans don't die anymore and that's caused something of a problem. Communication is instantaneous (over any distance) with devices similar to the Ansible in the Ender Quintet, but this system is much more distributed and doesn't have the whole "Ghost in the Machine" issue. Human space exploration hasn't been necessary as it's much simpler to send a drone to explore the galaxy than waste human lives in endless searching through countless star systems. After all, anyone can access a drone and "feel" what it's current status is. We (humans) know that the planet is dying and are building an interstellar "Ark" to take all of the humans, cold stored embryos of every animal and cold stored seeds (or cuttings) of all plant life. (Aside: Putting all of your "eggs" in one basket would be foolish, instead using the [[Square Degree Rule|https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_degree]] arc's are sent out through the universe to increase the chances of success. The humans will be in "Pods" for most of the journey that interface with a VR world similar, in concept, to the VR world in Ready Player One. I'm thinking the ship should be spherical with a drive system that moves in a gimbals around the spear. No silly artificial gravity but there may be warp/wormhole/hyperspace travel at some point, but not when the ark leaves Earth. On leaving the ark will be under power with plasma drives and probably harvest Saturn for hydrogen on it's way out of the Solar System (Maybe). I'm thinking that the "star voyage" should take at least a thousand years and be mostly uneventful, during the voyage everyone stays in their pod so no one is actually interacting with the real wold with their physical bodies but when the destination is reached (some calamity that wipes out most of the human life occurs, maybe 100 survivors?).

This is story happens soon after the apocalypse and the children are the direct progeny of our main character. They have some special abilities that they don't understand and they want help in figuring out who and what they are.

<<<







Modern technology has changed things a bit. Tactics themselves are the same no matter what development or technology achievements come along. So what are the basics of tactics? Knowledge of your tools, knowledge of your terrain and timing. That's all tactics really is. They say knowing is half the battle, but really... Knowledge is everything. When you "know" you can make a judgment. And don't forget, things change. Your knowledge will never be complete and what you know now may change in the next heartbeat

<<<








[[Hidden]]

Last night was sort of odd. I had an apiphony and I realized something. As much as it's nice and convenient to believe that I'm crazy, I'm not, not really. What I am is a story teller. I used to think that my creativity was a problem. Now I just realized that I needed to learn how to make use of it. The funny thing is, that I almost had a handle on it in the 3rd grade. But, then as things will, things changed. After the 3rd grade, my life was in a perpetual state of change. It's really only been recently that my life has had any semblance of order and structure, as weird as that sounds with the way I live my life. So, I'm a story teller. How does that work? Well, I have an experience and the outcome really doesn't matter, good or bad it's all the same, the future opens up to my mind and I tell a story about what happens next. Training my mind for strategy was probably on of the key points in developing this. In strategy, the goal is to think as far ahead of your opponents as possible. In chess, it's said that to be good, you need to be able to think through the next 8 moves on the board, before you make your next move. The more moves and the further out that you can anticipate increase your ability to avoid a trap and lure your opponents into one of your own. Well, telling a story is a lot like that. You have an idea and you follow it to a conclusion. With a story, your ability to think ahead and anticipate your opponent translates into the plot complexity that you can achieve. 






Where do ideas for a story come from? How does a story get made? Why do we even bother to write and tell stories? Really it's quite simple to answer all of those questions. A story is an effort to get people to understand or "see" something that we see in our minds eye. A story is to entertain and instruct at the same time. We write so that others can learn from us and so that we can get feedback from others without being attacked for our beliefs or thoughts. 






Aside from posterity, is there really any good reason to have our homes above ground? I can think of quite a few reasons to have housing below the ground. 

[[How to start]] 






[[Hidden]]

There is a huge problem, in reality, with people who are totally and completely reliable and dependable. They are always there for you and so you never miss them. You need someone to talk to? They are there. You need a ride somewhere? Call them up and they'll help. People who are utterly reliable and dependable are who you think of when there's an emergency. Someone who will be there to rescue you from the bad thing. Unfortunately, for those people, they always remind us of the bad things; what they rescued us from. We put them out of our minds when we're having fun. I don't think it's intentional. But, what are your rescuers doing when they aren't saving you? Do others wonder that they may be incredibly lonely or that the reason they are always there when you need them is that they care for you and want to be a part of your life? A part of your life outside of your need for them? No one likes being used and when there is that one person you turn to when you're in trouble, you're using that person; if that person isn't allowed in the rest of your life that is. 






I want to pierce your body. I want to take all of the pain, frustration, anger and sadness of the last five years and drive it into you. I want to take all of the negative in my life and pound it into your body. I want to build it up and fuck you hard until I release inside of you in a scalding rush of pleasure. I want your help to convert all the negative energy that's been eating my soul into positive energy.

Once the last drop is inside you, I want to hold you while our hearts slow and I want to be held in turn. I want gentle carresses and cuddles while we bask in the after-glow. I want to kiss your perfect lips and see your hair spread like a fan on my pilow with your eyes smiling at me, delving the depths of my soul.

When I have recovered my strength, I want to make gentle love to you. I want to watch you ride me. I want to feel you envelop me and watch as the pressure of pleasure builds in your every movement. When your body releases, I want to keep moving inside you and build the pleasure beyond what people think is possible. I want that shining golden nimbus of ectasy to envelop the both of us until we slip our skins and for a brief moment become that perfect pleasure that can only exist when a man and women are no longer just having sex or fucking and are instead making love.






[[Hidden]]

Someone once told me that "what if" is the dash between two dates on a tombstone. Well, I've lived my life. I hate it, but I've lived and I have no "what if's" in my life. I am far from happy but I refuse to submit to the status quo and lie down and live my life as a "good boy". I will fight every day of my existence to be, whatever that means, and I will leave this world a better place for my having survived. 






Well, I guess I can put this poem down again. Written in the TA room well after midnight on the graveyard shift during production of Stuart Little at Sony Pictures Imageworks in Culver City, California.
